So the golden ration looks like it's the best one,

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:11.960
but I want to show you on paper

00:07:11.960 --> 00:07:13.120
why it's the best one.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:14.580
And I'm going to do that by starting with Pi,

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:16.000
because, eh,
it's a good place to start.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:17.940
But Pi is an irrational number

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:19.700
that is apparently not very,

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:20.680
irrational.

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:21.980
And we kind of already know

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:23.060
that it's approximated well

00:07:23.460 --> 00:07:24.420
by a rational number.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:25.940
But let me show you how you can
sort of quantify that.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:27.320
So I'm going to say that Pi is

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:29.340
3 plus "a bit".

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:30.620
I don't think that's controversial.

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:31.500
But what I'm interested in is

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:32.540
writing this number Pi,

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:34.480
which I can never really write down in full,

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:35.920
which is why we have this symbol for it.

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:37.120
Can I write it in a way which

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:38.440
looks more like a fraction,

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:39.380
instead of like a decimal.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:40.900
And so 3 plus "a bit" isn't very helpful,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:41.760
but I could say,

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.540
since this bit is less than 1,

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:45.320
(other wise it would be 4 plus "a bit", right.)

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:46.260
Then I can say this is

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:48.420
3 plus 1 over "something".

