And I can find out what that

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:50.600
something is on a calculator.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:51.980
I could take away the 3,

00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:53.020
and I get the "something".

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:54.120
And then I can do 1 over that,

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:55.420
or x to the -1,

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:56.260
to find out what it is.

00:07:56.260 --> 00:07:57.860
And it actually is 7 point something.

00:07:57.860 --> 00:07:58.580
So I'm gonna write this,

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:00.220
1 over 7 plus "a bit".

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:01.660
The words "a bit" are not sort of

00:08:01.660 --> 00:08:03.180
mathematically recognised terminology,

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:03.840
but you get the idea.

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:04.520
So I could carry on,

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:06.980
I know this is 3 plus 1 over seven

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:07.860
plus "a bit".

00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:09.000
And I could write that as 1 over something.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:10.020
And that's on my screen now,

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:11.400
so I could take away the 7

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:13.300
and get the bit, 
and do 1 over that.

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:15.600
And I get 15 and "a bit".

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:17.500
I can start writing 15 plus "a bit",

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:18.460
and instead of doing the "a bit" now,

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:19.480
I'm just going to go straight in with

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:20.300
1 over something.

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:21.720
Take away 15,

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:22.820
get "the bit".

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:25.240
x to the -1.
Do one over it,

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:26.320
and I get 1,

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:27.500
and a bit.

00:08:27.940 --> 00:08:29.360
Take away 1, do the bit

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:30.880
It's a very small bit this time.

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:32.740
I'm going to get 292.

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:33.740
And you can see that if

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:35.220
this number is truly irrational,

00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:36.240
I can just keep going.

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:37.400
And actually, this thing here is called

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:39.260
the "Continued Fraction", for Pi.

00:08:39.260 --> 00:08:40.540
And something very obvious happens

00:08:40.540 --> 00:08:41.720
with Pi is that you get a

00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:42.640
very small number here,

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:44.140
and then you get a 
very large number here.

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:45.180
In the trade, 
they call it truncating,

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:46.920
but if you chop the continued fraction

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:47.540
at a certain point,

00:08:47.540 --> 00:08:48.840
you'll get an approximation.

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:51.360
So 3 and a seventh is 22/7,

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:52.780
is a good approximation for Pi.

00:08:52.780 --> 00:08:53.560
If you chop there,

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:54.740
you get an approximation.

00:08:54.740 --> 00:08:55.340
If you chop there,

00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:56.900
if you chop it there.

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:58.320
But because this number is massive,

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:00.160
and it's 1 over that number,

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:03.720
this additional bit is tiny.

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:05.220
[Brady] Becoming more and more trivial.

00:09:05.220 --> 00:09:08.040
Well, actually, after that it
 goes back to being some ones

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:08.900
in the continued fraction.

00:09:08.900 --> 00:09:10.440
But that particular point means

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:12.200
that you don't add very much accuracy

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:13.580
at those two levels of truncation

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:14.960
which means it was really accurate before,

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.160
which means the step before that

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:17.600
was ridiculously good.

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:19.460
Which means Pi is

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:22.000
well approximated quite early on

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:23.200
by a rational number.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:24.200
Which is why I'm going to claim

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:24.880
that it's not very irrational,

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:26.420
and why when you saw the diagram of it,

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:27.500
it looks like it had spokes.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:28.820
So, looking at the continued fraction,

00:09:28.820 --> 00:09:29.740
the question is,

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:31.600
"What would the most irrational number look like"?

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:33.100
It would be the one with the continued fraction

00:09:33.100 --> 00:09:34.840
that doesn't have any large numbers in it.

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:37.320
So I'm going to claim that this is a pretty good candidate.

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:37.880
Call it x,

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:39.360
but the continued fraction would be, well,

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:40.260
let's just start with 1,

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:41.320
but then the continued fraction

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:43.680
would go 1 over the smallest whole number.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:44.840
One.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:45.660
Then we'd have a one here,

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:46.880
and a one here,

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:48.080
and a one here,

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:50.200
and this is something that a lot of people do recognise.

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:51.520
It's an odd thing to ask what it is,

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:52.680
but whatever it is,

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:54.220
it will be badly approximated

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:55.200
any time you truncate it,

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:56.200
because these numbers are small.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:57.540
Now, just as a little heads up,

00:09:57.540 --> 00:09:59.580
I'm going to tell you that root 2

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:01.000
has a continued fraction as well.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:02.660
1 plus 1 over 2,

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:03.820
plus 1 over 2,

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:04.920
plus 1 over 2,

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:06.280
plus 1 over 2,

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:07.220
and carries on like that.

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:08.300
Which is incidentally why

00:10:08.300 --> 00:10:10.100
root 2 looked pretty good on our diagram.

00:10:10.100 --> 00:10:11.760
Because although these are not the smallest numbers,

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:13.640
they're consistent, and they stay small.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:14.980
Where I want to get to with this video,

00:10:14.980 --> 00:10:15.840
you might know the answer,

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:16.720
but I want to prove it, is:

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:18.300
What is this number?

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:19.380
I'm going to solve this.

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:20.640
This is an infinite thing,

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:22.000
but we can solve this surprisingly easy

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:23.420
because it carries on forever.

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:24.620
Let me point out something

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:25.500
which I think is obvious

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:26.980
when someone points it out,

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:28.040
which is that this thing,

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:29.500
is the same as the whole thing.

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:30.220
It is x.

00:10:30.220 --> 00:10:31.960
Which means I can sort of grab that thing

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:32.540
and call it x

00:10:32.540 --> 00:10:33.480
and I can rewrite this equation as

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:36.180
x equals 1 plus 1 over x.

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:38.600
And that looks much less scary.

00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:39.920
In fact it's a quadratic equation,

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:41.100
which I'm gonna solve.

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:42.840
I'm sure people watching this video

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:44.200
would have their favourite way
of solving quadratics.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:45.620
I'm going to do maybe

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:47.260
not quite the quadratic formula.

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:48.440
I've seen a friend of mine,

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:49.140
called Matt Parker,

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:50.500
try this with a quadratic formula.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:51.460
There's a better way,

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:52.960
I'm multiplying by x.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:55.440
To get x squared equals x plus 1.

00:10:55.460 --> 00:10:57.160
I'm going to rearrange it onto one side.

00:10:57.180 --> 00:11:00.320
I've got x squared minus x minus 1 equals 0.

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:01.620
At this point a lot of people reach

00:11:01.620 --> 00:11:02.640
for the quadratic formula.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:04.620
That minus B plus or minus 
the square root...

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:06.120
I'm going to complete the square,

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:07.920
which is where the formula comes from.

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:09.660
So I'm going to realise that if I write

00:11:09.660 --> 00:11:12.220
x minus a half, 
squared,

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:14.200
that would square to
 give me the x squared,

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:16.520
it would also give me
the minus x I need.

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:17.980
Try it if you don't believe it.

00:11:17.980 --> 00:11:19.220
But it will create a quarter,

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:19.960
which I don't want,

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:21.040
from the half squared.

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:22.920
And I've still got a minus 1 here.

00:11:23.660 --> 00:11:24.560
I'm just going to carry on,

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:26.500
putting this stuff on the other side.

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:29.360
I get x minus a half, 
squared, 
equals;

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:30.700
combining these,

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:32.360
I'm gonna get 5 over 4.

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:33.900
And now I can square root it.

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:35.280
This is the whole point of 
completing the square.

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:37.720
x minus a half equals

00:11:38.100 --> 00:11:40.300
plus or minus the square root of five

00:11:40.620 --> 00:11:41.760
because I square rooted the five)

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:43.140
over 2

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:44.420
because that's the square root of 4

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:45.820
And I'm gonna do one more step,

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:47.080
and this needs a box because,

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:48.360
x equals

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:50.800
Put this half on the other side,

00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:56.400
[Writing sounds]

00:11:56.400 --> 00:11:57.380
That's the same thing,

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:59.300
and this is equal to Phi.

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:00.780
Which is the Golden Ratio.

00:12:00.780 --> 00:12:02.080
And it is the most irrational number

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:03.440
because of the way it builds

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:04.300
as a continued fraction.

00:12:04.300 --> 00:12:06.320
Which is why it looks so nice

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:08.180
when you stack it round a sunflower.

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:10.040
And why it carves a path

00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:10.900
